<font color="#FF0000">HISTORICAL PERSPECTIVE.</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan  3 19:48:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I am a professional soldier so my perspective is a bit different.  Most Americans have very little historical perspective and so what happens to them is the most: horrible, wonderful, etc.<br>
 As a student of war, using any &quot;objective&quot; creiteria would show that Viet Nam doesn't even compare with Korea.  We lost almost the same number there in about three years  as we did in Viet Nam in ten.  WW2, WW1 all were much more destructive to both indaviduals and the social fabric.<br>
  The above comments concerning the treatment I and others received, is a very distictive feature of that conflect.<br>
   Add that when I was in Viet Nam, my wife received phone calls saying I was dead, or wishing that I would be killed or maimed.  That was a bit different.<br>
   There wasn't any &quot;Welcome Home Parade&quot; until about 15 years after the war.  I didn't go.  I didn't feel that my &quot;fellow citizens&quot; late welcome would do me much good.<br>
   War sucks---and is the second worst thing that can happen.<br>
   <br>

